{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deftab720\deflang2057{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil \fcharset0 Arial;}{\f1\fswiss Arial;}{\f2\fnil \fcharset2 WingDings;}{\f3\fswiss \fcharset0 Arial;}{\f4\fnil \fcharset0 Courier New;}}{\colortbl\red0\green0\blue0;\red0\green128\blue0;\red0\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}\pard \plain \plain\fs18\cf1 \protect <NS 1>\plain\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\fs22\cf3\b TPJCBViewer Example
\par \plain\fs8\cf2  \plain\fs18\cf1 \protect </NS 1>\plain\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 The following is an example of how to use the Clipboard Viewer Component.
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Drop a \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 2>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 TPJCBViewer\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 2>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  component, a TButton and a TMemo on a form. Do not change any of the components' default properties. Add the Clipbrd unit to your uses clause. Using the object inspector, create the following event handlers:
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \pard \fi-400 \li400 \tx400 \plain\f2\fs18\cf2 \'A7\plain\f3\fs18\cf2 \tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 an \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 3>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 OnClipboardChanged\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 3>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  handler for the TPJCBViewer component;
\par \plain\f2\fs18\cf2 \'A7\plain\f3\fs18\cf2 \tab \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 an OnClick handler for the button.
\par \pard \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Implement the event handlers as follows:
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf1 \protect <KP 4>\plain\f4\fs18\cf2\b procedure\plain\f4\fs18\cf2  TForm1.PJCBViewer1ClipboardChanged(Sender: TObject);
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf2\b begin\plain\f4\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf1   // Clipboard has changed - emit beep and decide whether to enable button
\par   // (only if text is on clipboard)
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf2   MessageBeep(0);
\par   Button1.Enabled := ClipBoard.HasFormat(CF_TEXT);
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf2\b end\plain\f4\fs18\cf2 ;
\par \plain\f4\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf2\b procedure\plain\f4\fs18\cf2  TForm1.Button1Click(Sender: TObject);
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf2\b begin\plain\f4\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf1   // We assume this button can only be clicked when there is text on clipboard,
\par   // so it is safe to display the text
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf2   Memo1.Text := ClipBoard.AsText;
\par \plain\f4\fs18\cf2\b end\plain\f4\fs18\cf2 ;\plain\f4\fs18\cf1 \protect </KP 4>\plain\f4\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 Because TPJCBViewer's \plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect <HS 5>\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 TriggerOnCreation\plain\f1\fs18\cf1 \protect </HS 5>\plain\f3\fs18\cf2  property\plain\f1\fs18\cf2  is true by default, an OnClipboardChanged event is triggered as the program starts.\plain\f3\fs18\cf2  The beep that is generated by the event handler proves this.\plain\f1\fs18\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs8\cf2 
\par \plain\f1\fs18\cf2 The button is enabled only if the clipboard contains text and becomes greyed out when the clipboard doesn't contain text. Clicking the button displays the clipboard text in the memo. Whenever the clipboard's contents change a beep is emitted. \plain\f0\fs18\cf2 
\par }

